    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6ee80d35-a46d-4221-ad8d-dc3fc8d236e1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a cheerful, energetic 9-year-old girl with bright brown eyes and long dark hair worn in two pigtails. She attends third grade at a local elementary school and loves drawing, playing with her two pet rabbits, and practicing gymnastics twice a week. Today, however, she appears visibly uncomfortable — her nose is red and raw from frequent blowing, her eyes are slightly watery, and she occasionally sneezes mid-sentence. She speaks in a noticeably nasal tone and keeps wiping her nose with a crumpled tissue clutched in her hand.\n\n{patientName} has been feeling unwell for the past three days. Her symptoms began with a scratchy, sore throat and progressed to a runny nose with clear, watery discharge that has since become slightly thicker and cloudy. She also complains of a mild headache and a feeling of pressure around her forehead and cheeks. She has been sneezing frequently and feels generally tired, preferring to rest on the couch rather than run around as usual. Her mother also notes that {patientName} has been snoring during sleep over the past two nights due to significant nasal congestion, and {patientName} herself mentions that her ears feel slightly \"full\" and she occasionally notices a faint ringing sound in them (tinnitus), which she describes as bothersome at bedtime.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her parents and a younger brother, aged 6, who started showing similar symptoms just yesterday. Several of her classmates were reportedly absent from school with cold-like symptoms over the past week, suggesting a community spread. Her mother brought her in today, concerned about her persistent symptoms and mild fever, and wants to make sure there is no secondary infection developing. As a school-going child in a classroom environment with 25 peers, {patientName} is routinely exposed to respiratory viruses circulating among children, representing a well-recognised risk factor for recurrent upper respiratory tract infections.\n\n{patientName} has a good appetite most days, though she has been eating less than usual due to nasal congestion making it harder to taste food. She sleeps approximately 9–10 hours per night but has been restless the past two nights due to nasal stuffiness and snoring. She is an otherwise active child who enjoys weekend bike rides with her family and reading adventure books before bedtime."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
